<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="Publisher" Owner="NLM"><PMID Version="1">41843724</PMID><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>17</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1423-0143</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month><Day>17</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Kidney &amp; blood pressure research</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Kidney Blood Press Res</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Chronic kidney disease, sarcopenia and hormonal-metabolic alterations: an intriguing association.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1</StartPage><EndPage>27</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1-27</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1159/000551499</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">Sarcopenia is a common yet underrecognized complication of chronic kidney disease (CKD), often affecting younger patients and progressing more rapidly than age-related muscle loss. It is driven by a combination of metabolic, hormonal, and inflammatory abnormalities associated with declining renal function.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="SUMMARY" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">This review outlines the key mechanisms linking CKD to sarcopenia, including metabolic acidosis, uremic toxin accumulation, hormonal dysregulation, insulin resistance, and chronic inflammation. These factors impair muscle protein turnover and promote protein-energy wasting (PEW). The review also discusses diagnostic limitations and emerging therapeutic strategies, such as individualized nutrition, resistance training, and gut microbiota modulation.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="KEY MESSAGES" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Sarcopenia in CKD contributes to increased morbidity and mortality. Early identification and personalized, multidisciplinary interventions are essential to preserve muscle health and improve patient outcomes.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>The Author(s). Published by S. Karger AG, Basel.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Quercia</LastName><ForeName>Alessandro Domenico</ForeName><Initials>AD</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Cavigiolo</LastName><ForeName>Beatrice</ForeName><Initials>B</Initials></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Mele</LastName><ForeName>Chiara</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType><PublicationType UI="D016454">Review</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>17</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Switzerland</Country><MedlineTA>Kidney Blood Press Res</MedlineTA><NlmUniqueID>9610505</NlmUniqueID><ISSNLinking>1420-4096</ISSNLinking></MedlineJournalInfo><CitationSubset>IM</CitationSubset></MedlineCitation><PubmedData><History><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="received"><Year>2025</Year><Month>7</Month><Day>30</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="accepted"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>9</Day></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="medline"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>18</Day><Hour>13</Hour><Minute>41</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="pubmed"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>18</Day><Hour>13</Hour><Minute>41</Minute></PubMedPubDate><PubMedPubDate PubStatus="entrez"><Year>2026</Year><Month>3</Month><Day>17</Day><Hour>14</Hour><Minute>24</Minute></PubMedPubDate></History><PublicationStatus>aheadofprint</PublicationStatus><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType="pubmed">41843724</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="doi">10.1159/000551499</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType="pii">000551499</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle></PubmedArticleSet>